Consider the collection ${A\_n}$ of all rational numbers in the interval $(0, 1)$ and let $X = \[0, 1]$. Let $f: X \to \mathbb{R}$ be the function defined by

$$f(x) = \begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } x \text{ is rational} \\
0 & \text{if } x \text{ is irrational}
\end{cases}$$

Each $A\_n$ is a closed set of rational numbers and the collection ${A\_n}$ is countable, but $f$ is not continuous at any point in $\[0, 1]$ as it jumps from $0$ to $1$ at every rational point.
